{
  "doc_id": "48457",
  "text": "Although ultrasound and CT are often combined to reveal and characterize most renal lesions, MR is sometimes required when indeterminate lesions are found [CITATION_1] , or when a hyperattenuating renal mass is observed on CT [CITATION_2] . Furthermore, some renal masses are incidentally discovered when MR imaging is performed to answer questions other than urology ones. On the other hand, MR imaging has been considered the most accurate method for those patients with contraindications to iodinated contrast administration such as in patients with renal failure and those with an allergy to iodinated contrast material [CITATION_3] .",
